WEBVTT

00:27.714 --> 00:31.000
Hey there heritage friends and family and guests.

00:31.100 --> 00:34.367
We are so glad that you have joined us for worship today.

00:34.767 --> 00:43.244
No matter if you're connecting on TV online, maybe you're there at Kiwani, we are so glad that you are with us today.

00:43.444 --> 00:48.754
It promises to be a phenomenal time of worship, of connecting with one another.

00:48.834 --> 00:50.957
engaging with the word singing.

00:51.097 --> 00:52.540
It's just going to be a phenomenal time.

00:52.580 --> 00:54.403
So we are glad that you are here.

00:54.443 --> 00:58.088
We're continuing in our unfiltered family series.

00:58.128 --> 00:59.310
And this is week three.

00:59.891 --> 01:03.797
And the last couple of weeks have been phenomenal messages.

01:03.877 --> 01:09.746
And so if you haven't been journeying along with us or maybe you're trying to understand maybe what all of this is about,

01:09.954 --> 01:21.009
I'd really encourage you to go to heritageqc.com slash watch and you can see some of these past messages and services because they've been really impactful for me and for so many others.

01:21.430 --> 01:25.296
But today, we're going to be stepping into a conversation about finances.

01:25.716 --> 01:32.946
And I know some of you right now may be reaching for the remote or trying to look for that pause button, but I really encourage you, don't miss this.

01:32.986 --> 01:38.514
This is not a conversation about how to get more of your money for anything that we are doing.

01:38.818 --> 01:53.381
The whole conversation is about finances and really that important piece of our lives and how we can best position ourselves and our finances for the best outcome for our families and for those around us.

01:53.862 --> 01:59.851
And so I really encourage you to continue just to stay connected as we have that great conversation.

02:00.553 --> 02:04.719
Now, many of you have been hopefully maybe watching the Olympics.

02:05.160 --> 02:06.482
It's a great time of

02:06.658 --> 02:21.612
seeing all of the great athletes from around the world coming together, putting everything they have on the line, on the track, on the court, whatever sport you may be into to see how best they stack up against the rest of the world.

02:21.652 --> 02:24.615
And so I hope you've been enjoying that as I have.

02:25.175 --> 02:34.945
But as I've been watching these athletes give everything that they have, it reminded me of this verse in Hebrews chapter 12.

02:35.445 --> 02:36.306
It says this,

02:36.834 --> 02:51.133
Therefore, since we are surrounded by such a great cloud of witnesses, let us throw off everything that hinders the sin that so easily entangles and let us run with perseverance, the race marked out for us.

02:51.594 --> 03:06.354
Let us fix our eyes on Jesus, the author and the perfecter of our faith, who for the joy set before him endured the cross, scorning at shame and sat down at the right hand of the throne.

03:06.722 --> 03:07.263
of God.

03:08.224 --> 03:14.592
And so I see these athletes who have given so much all of their lives towards this end goal.

03:14.712 --> 03:20.259
And that is the call I thank for each one of us to throw off everything to continue to pursue Jesus.

03:20.760 --> 03:23.904
To continue just to say, I am here for you God.

03:24.044 --> 03:28.770
I want to understand what you have for my life and I want to give everything to you.

03:28.810 --> 03:32.274
So let us just throw off everything we have here today.

03:32.578 --> 03:47.286
Let us let go of the worries of the different things happening in the world around us and focus in to the author, the perfecter, the one who begins and who finishes our faith, our Lord, our Savior, Jesus Christ.

03:47.787 --> 03:49.330
Let's worship Him together.

14:34.370 --> 14:35.571
Wanna speak?

19:18.274 --> 19:26.783
You know, as we've been leaning into this conversation about family and who God is inviting us to be in our families, however that's defined, whatever it looks like for us.

19:27.364 --> 19:42.941
And even as we just sang, where we're declaring the power and the life of Jesus into those family spaces, I'm reminded that when Jesus spoke to his father, our father, God, he had a close-in relationship.

19:42.961 --> 19:47.026
He, in fact, called him Abba Father, Daddy.

19:48.194 --> 20:02.945
It's an invitation and a reminder for me and for you that whatever our earthly family looks like, we have a Heavenly Father who invites us into so much more, who cares for us, who desires more for us than we can imagine for ourselves.

20:03.005 --> 20:07.314
In fact, that's how Scripture describes some of God's intent and invitation for us.

20:07.650 --> 20:20.357
So I'm not sure what it is that you're facing this week or this month or what's going on in your own family dynamic spaces where you feel super excited about what's there, some spaces where maybe you're grieving a bit.

20:21.159 --> 20:26.290
I'm reminded of a passage of scripture that actually is a father speaking to his son.

20:26.594 --> 20:31.841
And I believe it's the voice of God speaking to us as his sons and daughters.

20:32.221 --> 20:37.188
This is what he says in Proverbs chapter 4 verses 11 and following.

20:37.228 --> 20:45.018
It says, When you walk, your steps will not be hampered.

20:45.318 --> 20:47.081
When you run, you will not stumble.

20:47.782 --> 20:49.404
Hold on to instruction.

20:49.544 --> 20:50.846
Do not let it go.

20:51.406 --> 20:52.247
Guard it well.

20:52.748 --> 20:54.290
For it is your life.

20:54.850 --> 21:01.457
In just a few moments, we're going to be pressing into God's word together as Pastor Josh unpacked some great teaching for us.

21:01.477 --> 21:12.810
And my prayer for you and for me is that we would be led by our Father down the paths of wisdom and that we would hold on to this instruction, understanding it is the way of life for us.

21:13.871 --> 21:23.602
In fact, I'm going to pray for us now and invite you to bring your own petitions and needs before our Father who cares so much, even as we prepare to press into this time of teaching today.

21:24.290 --> 21:26.353
So let's pray.

21:26.373 --> 21:30.198
Father, you are a good father.

21:30.919 --> 21:35.926
Your word reminds us that you lead us down the way of life and wisdom.

21:36.727 --> 21:44.518
And for my friends, I pray that you would allow them to entrust you with all of those spaces in their lives where they need wisdom today.

21:45.119 --> 21:47.282
In fact, we lay them before you right now.

21:53.474 --> 22:01.743
We ask you to speak to us in terms of what it looks like for us to be faithful in our families, whatever that looks like, where we're celebrating and where we're grieving.

22:02.684 --> 22:04.446
And we lay those things before you write that, too.

22:09.432 --> 22:13.176
And finally, we ask you, lead us in the way we should go.

22:13.517 --> 22:16.981
Show us the path of life through the teaching of your work.

22:17.802 --> 22:21.746
Allow us to be open and honest with you and with ourselves.

22:22.114 --> 22:28.001
as you speak to us about us in our relationship with you and the Father.

22:28.021 --> 22:29.003
Lead us now, we pray.

22:29.744 --> 22:34.510
In Jesus' name, amen.

22:34.530 --> 22:49.388
I started to notice the problem one day when I walked outside and I saw my neighbor's new car.

22:49.409 --> 22:50.610
That was a real wake up call for me.

23:03.490 --> 23:07.216
Who knew that inside that small box was the very thing I had been looking for this whole time.

23:07.918 --> 23:09.981
The illusion of having everything that I want.

23:11.524 --> 23:14.228
I used to ask my friends how their kids were so well behaved.

23:14.709 --> 23:17.234
Now my friends are coming to me with the same question.

23:18.295 --> 23:19.297
I'll never call.

23:22.382 --> 23:26.770
Why see life for what it is when you can see it through the life filter?

23:34.658 --> 23:40.327
Well, hey, friends, I am so glad that each of you are plugging in and connecting with us today.

23:40.387 --> 23:45.616
Regardless of where you're watching this from, I am so glad that you've taken time to worship.

23:46.096 --> 23:50.103
And we just continue to pray that God will do something great in our time together.

23:50.443 --> 23:54.610
And we've been in the midst of a series called Unfiltered Family.

23:54.754 --> 23:58.038
And it's been such a meaningful series to me personally so far.

23:58.618 --> 24:01.842
Both of our communicators so far in the series have done great job.

24:02.122 --> 24:04.845
Pastor Jeremiah launched us into the series two weeks ago.

24:05.326 --> 24:09.310
And then last week, Pastor Steve Norman did a great job of continuing the conversation.

24:09.350 --> 24:13.174
And I just want you to know if you missed either of those two messages, you can check those out.

24:13.194 --> 24:24.146
You can get caught up at heritageqc.com and you can click the watch button at the top of the screen and get caught up in this conversation that we're going to be having for the next couple of weeks.

24:24.322 --> 24:27.149
So unfiltered family, that's kind of where we're going today.

24:27.270 --> 24:35.371
I've been tasked with continuing this conversation around the topic of, wait for it, wait for it, drum roll finances.

24:35.992 --> 24:39.060
Yeah, we're going to just pull the Band-Aid off quickly, right?

24:39.080 --> 24:41.266
We're going to talk about money today.

24:41.506 --> 24:48.937
And right out front, I should mention that I appreciate the verbiage that we've chosen for this series title.

24:49.017 --> 25:09.288
When we talk about unfiltered, that it's a very appropriate kind of word to use in an age where it is extremely easy and tempting to sort of curate the perfect stories and the perfect images to post on social media in order to project a certain image of how your family operates.

25:09.769 --> 25:10.770
But you should know

25:11.042 --> 25:21.338
that I have a 15 year old son who for years has served as our personal family unfiltered on Facebook.

25:21.359 --> 25:27.629
And what I mean by that is that he for many years has refused to take a decent family photo.

25:28.089 --> 25:30.433
We ask him to smile, he will not smile.

25:30.453 --> 25:38.546
It doesn't matter what you say or what you do, he just stands there with no expression, maybe sometimes even worse, but he just

25:38.626 --> 25:41.272
He just won't comply with the request.

25:41.733 --> 25:44.839
In fact, consider Exhibit A from a few years ago.

25:45.420 --> 25:46.383
Yep, no smile.

25:46.964 --> 25:49.770
Consider Exhibit B from this past year.

25:49.830 --> 25:51.794
Still, no smile.

25:52.290 --> 25:59.017
So in early June, we as a family, we got to take a trip that we had been kind of holding out on for a long time.

25:59.037 --> 26:04.663
We were able to go to Florida, go to Disney World and check out to Star Wars Land and all that stuff.

26:04.683 --> 26:05.464
It was a great trip.

26:05.865 --> 26:13.293
But early on in that trip, we discovered that my son had made a financially binding contract with my mom.

26:13.953 --> 26:18.378
She had texted him early on in this trip and she extended this offer to him.

26:18.438 --> 26:22.162
She said, Aaron, for every picture that you

26:22.338 --> 26:32.868
For every picture that is posted on Facebook by your mom that has you legitimately smiling in it, I will give you $10 up to five pictures.

26:33.408 --> 26:38.413
So 50 bucks is what she was offering for this compliance.

26:38.433 --> 26:41.496
And so we strategically picked all of our spots.

26:41.556 --> 26:45.980
We got pictures at all of the four Disney theme parks.

26:46.020 --> 26:47.582
We got a really great one at the beach.

26:47.622 --> 26:50.284
In fact, consider Exhibit C, right?

26:50.525 --> 26:51.986
This is a much

26:52.130 --> 26:53.312
better picture.

26:53.913 --> 26:55.936
But I want us to do a little bit of math here, okay?

26:55.976 --> 27:03.367
Because let's be generous and estimate that it took Aaron about 10 seconds per picture to offer his smile.

27:03.888 --> 27:10.859
That's a working wage of $60 a minute and about $3,600 an hour.

27:10.979 --> 27:13.643
I mean, that's not a bad first job.

27:13.824 --> 27:17.850
I think I made like $7.50 in my first job.

27:18.290 --> 27:20.594
And that's a good gig.

27:20.994 --> 27:25.598
But then in the background, there's my daughter, Emily, who has always been compliant.

27:25.979 --> 27:27.340
She's always been respectful.

27:27.380 --> 27:28.942
She's always been helpful and kind.

27:29.482 --> 27:33.166
And by the way, has this light up the room kind of smile.

27:33.806 --> 27:36.028
And she's watching all of this take place.

27:36.209 --> 27:38.591
And she's like, okay, where's my 50 bucks?

27:38.851 --> 27:44.457
I've been lending my smile to pictures ever since 2002 with no complaint.

27:44.617 --> 27:46.038
Where's my reward for that?

27:46.659 --> 27:48.180
So there you go, right?

27:48.560 --> 27:50.162
Family and money.

27:50.370 --> 27:52.373
always a great combination, right?

27:52.914 --> 27:54.376
Maybe not, maybe not always.

27:55.038 --> 27:57.502
So that's our journey today, right?

27:57.682 --> 28:04.232
And we should just go ahead and own right from the very beginning the complexity of talking about finances.

28:04.793 --> 28:08.459
That finances can be triggering, it can be traumatic, it can be emotional.

28:08.880 --> 28:15.090
In fact, I just read an article this week written by Les and Leslie Parrot, who are marriage experts

28:15.746 --> 28:25.256
And through their research and through the conversations that they've had, they put finances in the top five trigger kind of tension triggers in a marriage, top five.

28:25.416 --> 28:29.221
That's not really a surprise, but it's eye opening for us to understand.

28:29.861 --> 28:33.425
And look, it doesn't matter if you're married or single.

28:33.765 --> 28:36.288
It doesn't matter if you have kids, grandkids, no kids.

28:36.929 --> 28:42.094
If you are currently breathing, finances and money have ripple in your life.

28:42.735 --> 28:45.458
It's something we all have to navigate

28:45.634 --> 28:46.435
and deal with.

28:47.056 --> 28:53.684
And I know that for many of us, we sort of put finances on sort of a list with politics and sex as taboo topics.

28:53.704 --> 28:55.366
We should not talk about this.

28:55.867 --> 29:00.353
And I get it, some of you might even be feeling like, you know, where's the nearest exit?

29:00.413 --> 29:03.657
Or how can I turn this off as quick as possible?

29:04.098 --> 29:07.121
But I want to just encourage you to lean in.

29:07.182 --> 29:13.810
Because if money is something that touches all of us, then I think it's worth exploring.

29:13.922 --> 29:16.765
exactly what God has to say about it.

29:17.385 --> 29:20.729
And that being said, I want to own just one other thing before we really get going.

29:21.209 --> 29:23.831
And that's just to say, I'm not a financial expert.

29:24.372 --> 29:25.733
I'm not a financial planner.

29:26.514 --> 29:41.008
And so what I'm really hoping to do is to kind of provide a theology of money and to give us a framework from which we can start taking steps and making decisions with our money that will really honor God.

29:42.009 --> 29:43.250
So allow me to start by

29:43.330 --> 29:50.978
addressing two myths that I've seen attached to money, two kind of spiritual myths that I've seen attached.

29:50.998 --> 29:57.024
And in this, I've seen kind of attached throughout church history, I've seen it just in church in general.

29:57.485 --> 30:04.172
These two myths, I think are, as I look at them, they're sort of situated in opposite poles, they're kind of opposite reactions from one another.

30:04.612 --> 30:08.856
But I think it's important that we avoid either end of this spectrum.

30:09.257 --> 30:10.418
So here's the first myth.

30:10.850 --> 30:13.635
that money is the root of all evil.

30:14.757 --> 30:15.759
Money is the root of all evil.

30:15.779 --> 30:16.881
Now, I hear this a lot.

30:16.942 --> 30:21.831
Maybe many of you have as well, but it's actually a misquote from the Scriptures.

30:22.252 --> 30:32.772
The actual statement given by Paul in 1 Timothy goes like this, for the love of money is the root of all kinds of evil.

30:33.754 --> 30:34.034
Now,

30:34.306 --> 30:41.015
This might seem like a pretty small and insignificant nuance, but listen, the implications are actually pretty big.

30:41.576 --> 30:48.826
See, it's either on one hand, it's either money itself is completely evil and should be avoided at all, you know, all costs.

30:48.846 --> 30:54.313
Or as Paul writes, it's actually the obsession of money that can lead to evil.

30:54.713 --> 30:58.439
It's the love of money that can lead to problem things.

30:59.180 --> 31:01.042
And there's a huge difference in this.

31:01.186 --> 31:13.397
And it's important to resolve because there's been a segment of people in church history that have taken the approach that all money, all possessions, all material items, all of those things are just inherently evil.

31:14.058 --> 31:20.524
And so they determined that the earning of money, the collection of items, all of that should be avoided.

31:20.564 --> 31:26.310
And in fact, poverty can be looked at like a virtue to pursue.

31:26.350 --> 31:30.994
But that's actually not what Paul is saying here

31:31.074 --> 31:40.146
in this passage, he's stating that we can fall so in love with the earning and hoarding and spending of money that we actually turn all of this stuff into an idol.

31:40.947 --> 31:43.550
And it's an idol that can become all-consuming.

31:44.111 --> 31:51.160
It's an idol that can tempt us to trade character and honesty and even relationship for the sake of earning more and getting more.

31:51.861 --> 31:58.770
Now Paul is not saying that money itself is bad and as such that he's not saying that earning money is bad.

31:59.266 --> 32:00.948
Learning how to make money work for you.

32:00.988 --> 32:01.768
That's not bad.

32:01.829 --> 32:03.911
Providing for your family, that's not bad.

32:04.351 --> 32:07.234
Buying a couch, going on vacation, those things aren't bad.

32:07.834 --> 32:10.577
Listen, money itself is neither good nor bad.

32:10.737 --> 32:11.618
It just is.

32:12.379 --> 32:19.426
Like so much of our life, our response to things determine whether we're engaging with it in healthy or unhealthy ways.

32:19.486 --> 32:24.771
This is true of sex, of anger, of food, of hobbies, of a variety of other things.

32:24.851 --> 32:27.634
Those things are not bad in and of themselves.

32:27.714 --> 32:33.262
But all of those things can be abused or misused or set up as more important than God.

32:34.003 --> 32:36.226
And the life that God is calling us into.

32:37.107 --> 32:42.414
And so that's kind of the first myth that to say that money itself is the root of all evil.

32:42.474 --> 32:44.777
That is an untrue statement.

32:45.738 --> 32:55.151
But now I want to take you to kind of the opposite end of the spectrum and kind of deal with the second myth that I've heard throughout my time in ministry.

32:55.672 --> 32:57.234
And I would sum this up by saying that

32:57.602 --> 33:02.089
that the myth is monetary wealth is a sign of God's blessing.

33:03.432 --> 33:09.682
I've heard this communicated or at very least implied hundreds of times in my own ministry career.

33:09.782 --> 33:12.507
I've heard this way of thinking called the prosperity gospel.

33:13.168 --> 33:21.682
And the gist of this argument is that God will bless the faithful with everything that they want and need specifically in the realm of finances.

33:21.858 --> 33:31.790
And of course, the flip side to this, and it's sort of the dark shadow side of this, is that if your bank account isn't big enough, then it's indicative that your faith isn't big enough.

33:32.511 --> 33:36.455
And friends, listen, oh my goodness, that is dangerous theology.

33:36.996 --> 33:39.059
That is shaming theology.

33:39.539 --> 33:45.266
And when you look at the wholeness of the Scriptures, it is hard to make that argument stick.

33:45.570 --> 33:52.798
that God uses both people with mains and without mains to do really amazing things throughout the entirety of the scriptures.

33:52.858 --> 33:57.583
He used wealthy kings and he used poor nomadic prophets.

33:57.663 --> 34:02.048
He used white collar tax collectors and he used blue collar fishermen.

34:02.469 --> 34:14.322
I mean, if wealth equals God's blessing friends, it sure doesn't seem like maybe Jesus would have been blessed because it sure seems like he lived a pretty simple and frugal life, making ends meet certainly.

34:14.530 --> 34:28.405
but never having surplus, that the prosperity gospel kind of reminds me of treating God like this genie in the bottle and looking at prayer, like it's getting three wishes and just getting whatever you want.

34:29.486 --> 34:39.076
It's interesting that Jesus makes a statement in his sermon on the Mount that I think connects to this, kind of indirectly connects to us, but he makes the following observation.

34:39.777 --> 34:44.242
He says, for he, speaking of God, he gives his sunlight to both evil

34:44.674 --> 34:50.047
and the good, and he sends rain on the just and the unjust alike.

34:50.990 --> 34:57.586
Now listen, in context, he's not even talking about money here, but the principle is helpful for us, that good things happen

34:57.666 --> 35:00.069
to both good people and bad people.

35:00.489 --> 35:03.673
And bad things happen to both bad people and good people.

35:04.053 --> 35:10.861
And connected to that is to say that there are some wealthy people who are believers and some who are not.

35:10.961 --> 35:14.045
And this is true all the way down the economic scale.

35:14.405 --> 35:18.750
It is untrue to say that monetary wealth is a sign of God's blessing.

35:19.211 --> 35:25.778
That's just not the way that God operates in this world as demonstrated throughout the entirety of the scriptures.

35:26.146 --> 35:27.769
Now listen, why do I share this?

35:28.169 --> 35:29.652
What's the big deal with this?

35:29.952 --> 35:44.756
And I think it's mostly because it's somewhere between these two myths that we need to journey and walk as believers, that we're not called as a general principle to intentional poverty, particularly as we understand that money itself is not evil.

35:45.277 --> 35:51.026
We're certainly called to sacrifice, but I don't think we need to be allergic to finances or money.

35:51.714 --> 36:03.991
We should also, on the other side, not make the mistake of assuming that monetary wealth is a sign of blessing because that sort of actually elevates money and finances to almost idle status.

36:04.732 --> 36:07.616
And so the sweet spot is in between all of this.

36:08.057 --> 36:12.663
We don't have to disparage money, but we should not elevate it as an idle either.

36:13.464 --> 36:20.434
So I suppose that I personally would sum up the sweet spot, at least practically speaking, by encouraging us

36:20.610 --> 36:26.780
into two things, encouraging us to be intentional and encouraging us to be generous.

36:27.581 --> 36:33.531
I recall reading a sermon given by John Wesley way back in the 1700s and he makes the statement.

36:33.571 --> 36:37.938
He says, earn all you can, save all you can, give all you can.

36:38.210 --> 36:46.458
And he was asking those early methods to be fiscally responsible, but to be fiscally responsible with an eye towards being generous.

36:46.858 --> 36:53.304
In fact, he made a statement that he thought some of those early methods were really good at those first two points, but they had forgotten the third one.

36:53.965 --> 37:03.033
And he talked about the importance of making sure that when you're earning and saving, that you're always keeping an eye towards that generosity piece.

37:03.794 --> 37:05.335
So let me kind of break that down.

37:05.395 --> 37:06.617
Those two words.

37:06.637 --> 37:08.178
Let me start with the word intentional.

37:08.738 --> 37:17.211
Now, I know the word intentional has been overused over the last five, 10 years, but I really do think it's right as it relates to our money.

37:17.251 --> 37:19.915
The series is called unfiltered, right?

37:19.975 --> 37:25.964
So, allow me to be very unfiltered with you, very honest with you about my own story.

37:26.385 --> 37:31.873
Melissa, my wife and I, we made a ton of financial mistakes in our 20s.

37:31.993 --> 37:35.378
I mean, really, if there was a mistake to be made, I feel like we made it,

37:35.458 --> 37:38.447
We got into some pretty significant credit card debt.

37:38.889 --> 37:44.105
We took out two pretty ill-advised loans, and we just didn't understand how money worked at all.

37:44.205 --> 37:45.810
We just didn't know.

37:46.050 --> 37:49.436
And in our early 30s, we started to really look for help.

37:49.456 --> 37:51.840
We got very intentional about looking for help.

37:51.860 --> 37:53.282
We took a Ron Blue class.

37:53.322 --> 37:55.025
We took a Dave Ramsey class.

37:55.045 --> 37:56.988
I started reading books on the topic.

37:57.369 --> 38:00.454
We reached out and visited a financial planner.

38:00.875 --> 38:07.826
And through all of these various pieces of advice, we started to kind of scale out and stick to a monthly budget.

38:07.970 --> 38:14.263
We started to be strategic about debt repayment by using kind of Dave Ramsey's debt snowball method.

38:14.724 --> 38:21.277
We created an emergency fund and we just started working steps towards financial freedom and health.

38:22.279 --> 38:29.394
And along the way, when we didn't know something, we just started to ask for help from people who knew more than us.

38:29.602 --> 38:45.106
And I remember shortly after making these significant changes in our own kind of financial world, telling people that it actually felt like both of us had gotten significant raises when in fact neither of us were earning any more money.

38:45.406 --> 38:50.354
What had changed is that we were way more aware of what was coming in and what was going out.

38:50.466 --> 38:51.888
and what it was going out for.

38:51.948 --> 38:53.271
We were working the plan.

38:53.691 --> 39:01.625
We were tightening our belt and there was less impulsive spending that was happening and it helped us to be way more intentional.

39:02.326 --> 39:10.279
Now listen, I understand that every single person who is hearing me talk about this, you guys are, you're all in different financial places.

39:10.860 --> 39:11.621
So hear me on this.

39:12.242 --> 39:15.027
I am not trying to be specifically prescriptive here.

39:15.568 --> 39:16.850
My encouragement to you

39:17.218 --> 39:36.931
And really to all of us is that we just become more aware and more intentional of how we are leveraging and caretaking our resources, that you would journey with Holy Spirit and ask Him to sort of give you discernment and wisdom and that you would just take the next step, whatever that next step needs to be for you.

39:36.972 --> 39:40.818
If you're in a bind right now, like we were,

39:41.090 --> 39:49.600
I want you to understand there is no shame in asking for help to ask to be mentored by someone who knows a little bit more about money than maybe you do.

39:49.960 --> 39:58.290
For some of you, maybe the next step is just simply set a budget, watch the money that's coming in, watch the money that's going out, working a debt plan.

39:58.810 --> 40:09.042
Regardless of where you currently are standing financially, just my encouragement is take the next intentional step towards a healthier approach to finances.

40:09.410 --> 40:14.137
Now, the second word that I would encourage just to lean into is the word generous.

40:14.979 --> 40:18.885
I think a great framing story is found in Luke 21, verses one through four.

40:18.925 --> 40:19.966
Listen to this, this is great.

40:20.587 --> 40:26.456
While Jesus was in the temple, he watched the rich people dropping their gifts in the collection box.

40:27.257 --> 40:31.624
Then a poor widow came by and dropped in two small coins.

40:32.526 --> 40:38.034
I tell you the truth, Jesus said, this poor widow has given more than all the rest of them.

40:38.818 --> 40:48.291
for they have given a tiny part of their surplus, but she, poor as she is, has given everything she has.

40:49.373 --> 40:58.706
I remember learning about the story in Sunday School as a kid, and always being drawn in by that generous spirit, that demonstration of sacrifice.

40:58.818 --> 41:12.152
And it's really a great example of how Jesus would surprise people by his observations and by his teaching, by sort of flipping expectations and forcing people to look at something through a different lens.

41:12.713 --> 41:28.370
In this case, he wanted them to look less at the total amount given and much more at the ratio that he praised the widow for her extreme form of sacrifice because she gave 100%

41:28.706 --> 41:42.807
of what she had, compared to the other people might have given way more than her in terms of just the actual amount, but the ratios were way off and the sacrifice level was minimal compared to what the widow gave.

41:43.849 --> 41:53.263
And it's actually a great reminder for us in the same way that Jesus was generous to us by giving all of himself so that we might be saved.

41:53.884 --> 41:58.130
So we are called to live lives of radical generosity.

41:58.434 --> 42:03.870
Choosing to be generous, friends, it's actually not a financial decision first and foremost.

42:04.272 --> 42:05.776
It's a spiritual decision.

42:06.639 --> 42:09.227
It's that spiritual decision working with Holy Spirit.

42:10.350 --> 42:12.978
Every January, I have this ritual.

42:13.762 --> 42:21.169
where I go to our kind of, we have a cabinet where we keep all of our financial documents and I kind of go in and I clean that out.

42:21.349 --> 42:34.742
I shred documents that are old enough to be shred, creating space for the next year and Melissa and I will sort of go through all of our receipts and put some in like our tax folder so that we're ready for taxes whenever we get going on that.

42:35.142 --> 42:41.088
And just in general, we spend a few hours just cleaning up all of our documents.

42:41.108 --> 42:43.250
And in every year that I do this,

42:43.490 --> 42:48.695
I get to revisit sort of all of the things that we have purchased as a family over the last year.

42:48.755 --> 42:52.799
And sometimes the receipts would sort of bring back a good memory, right?

42:52.839 --> 43:01.868
Maybe we went to a ballgame together or maybe there was a holiday meal that, you know, a receipt sort of reminded us of a good time with family.

43:01.888 --> 43:05.471
And then there's other receipts that would remind you of painful times.

43:05.511 --> 43:12.658
Maybe it's a hospital receipt or a medical bill or something where you just remember that there was pain in that moment.

43:13.346 --> 43:18.131
Some of the receipts that I interact with lead me straight into buyer's remorse.

43:19.172 --> 43:20.513
You kind of ask, what?

43:21.174 --> 43:25.178
I spent that much on that thing that is already broken.

43:25.298 --> 43:28.962
Usually it was like some plastic thing that we bought the kids when they were younger.

43:29.022 --> 43:31.364
Why did I waste money on that?

43:31.384 --> 43:33.747
That the buyer's remorse would set in.

43:34.587 --> 43:41.074
But these beginning of the year sessions remind me that I have enough means that I

43:41.314 --> 43:47.042
I rarely need to say no on purchasing something that I need or even want.

43:47.823 --> 43:53.371
And often God will check my spirit in those moments of kind of an audit.

43:54.192 --> 44:02.343
And it turns into this unexpected spiritual exercise where he asks me to evaluate my own sacrifice level.

44:03.064 --> 44:10.194
And so I'm forced to ask the question, how do I respond in obedience when God nudges me to give?

44:10.722 --> 44:21.252
When I look at my total expenses and all of those receipts, is it clear that I am putting his purposes first in my life?

44:22.093 --> 44:23.795
Do I give generously to his kingdom?

44:24.856 --> 44:25.456
Here's a question.

44:26.097 --> 44:34.825
If someone were to look through all of my receipts and expenses over the course of a full year, would they actually see Jesus in that?

44:36.006 --> 44:37.728
And would they see radical generosity?

44:37.788 --> 44:39.730
Would they see sacrifice?

44:40.194 --> 44:43.157
It's always a sobering exercise.

44:43.838 --> 44:47.662
Sometimes I discern a lack of purpose over the course of the last year.

44:47.722 --> 44:52.587
And sometimes I could maybe point to a celebration moment where I did the right thing.

44:52.647 --> 44:58.973
But it seems like God always uses that annual review as a way to get my attention.

44:59.994 --> 45:07.602
And in turn, I would sort of spend some of those questions to you and to consider your own life, your own resources.

45:07.714 --> 45:15.947
your own expenses and receipts evaluation kind of a thing and just simply ask Holy Spirit to lead you in your next step of obedience.

45:16.428 --> 45:20.214
Where can you demonstrate a more radical generosity?

45:20.574 --> 45:28.086
Where can you leverage your resources, your time, your talent, your treasure to help the kingdom for greater impact?

45:29.027 --> 45:31.391
Friends, money is never an easy topic.

45:31.952 --> 45:35.858
Taking a spiritual view of our resources, that's never easy.

45:36.258 --> 45:38.661
because it calls us to relinquish control.

45:38.721 --> 45:42.726
And we just, oh my goodness, just naturally fight against that as humans.

45:43.567 --> 45:56.023
But at the end of the day, it really is, it's a matter of trust and perspective as we seek to spend and invest our lives into the things that will actually last for an eternity.

45:56.884 --> 46:04.754
And so my prayer for you, my prayer for me is that we begin to leverage our resources, but not idolize them.

46:05.282 --> 46:10.228
that we would seek to be intentional about our resources, but not flippant or careless.

46:11.029 --> 46:23.185
Let's seek to grow our muscles of radical generosity so that the world might see and experience Jesus through the way we steward and invest our resources.

46:24.366 --> 46:25.268
Would you pray with me?

46:28.191 --> 46:33.458
Lord, we approach your throne today with differing

46:34.178 --> 46:40.908
financial portfolios and different wages and different ways of seeing and interacting with with money.

46:42.070 --> 46:45.195
But we're all impacted by finances.

46:45.215 --> 46:56.593
So Lord, help us to find that sweet spot of obedience and that as people watch our lives, may they see that we are not controlled or obsessed with money.

46:56.633 --> 47:00.178
That money is not an idol for us.

47:01.218 --> 47:09.968
that we're not allergic to it or reject it, but rather that they would see that we are people led by you and your purposes.

47:10.008 --> 47:18.538
So help us to trust you and to incrementally step into fuller obedience in a more radical form of generosity.

47:19.899 --> 47:29.170
Jesus, you demonstrated the most radical form of generosity and love the world has ever seen when you gave your life on the cross.

47:30.018 --> 47:31.680
so that we might be safe from our sins.

47:32.902 --> 47:41.053
Help us, Lord, to model that same courage and love and generosity that we saw in you.

47:42.214 --> 47:43.957
We pray these things in Jesus' name.

47:45.459 --> 47:45.799
Amen.

47:53.029 --> 47:59.698
You were the word at the beginning, one with God.

48:58.978 --> 48:59.891
Jesus, you

49:33.442 --> 49:41.234
I never see

57:39.618 --> 57:42.242
day it has been as we have worshiped together.

57:42.803 --> 57:50.875
Learning what God invites us into as we look at what it meant and means to invest in ourselves and in those around us.

57:51.737 --> 57:57.325
If you haven't already I would really encourage you to step into and click on to HeritageQC.com.

57:57.505 --> 58:05.778
It's a website for our church that gives you all sorts of resources to be able to invest again into yourself and to those around you can find

58:05.922 --> 58:11.011
Note guys with discussion questions so you can dive deeper into the content of our messages.

58:11.071 --> 58:15.178
There's resources for your family, for kids of all ages.

58:15.538 --> 58:17.261
There's places where you can give.

58:17.321 --> 58:19.645
There's places to connect into group life.

58:20.186 --> 58:26.617
All sorts of different ways so that you can grow in your own relationship with Jesus Christ.

58:27.138 --> 58:32.146
You can find all of that and more also on our church center app.

58:32.450 --> 58:44.156
the heart behind both of those places to help you connect to God, to others, and to your purpose as you continue to chase him in the places that he has invited you towards as you invest in yourself and those along with you.

58:44.457 --> 58:46.962
Have a great rest of your week.

